§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ If we have a norm, then we have a metric. ⦉
⦉

§ Motivating result ⦉
<statement type='proposition'>
  ‖ Let $(V, F)$ be a vector space. ⦉

  ‖ Let $f: V → 𝗥$ be a norm. ⦉

  ‖ Let $g: V × V → 𝗥$ such that
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ g(x, y) = \norm{x - y}. ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ Then $g$ is a metric.
    † ⦊
      ‖ Future editions will include an account. ⦉
    ⦉⦉
</statement>
